Anonymous Sun 12 Sep 2021 20:16:20 No.41592503 Report
Quoted By: >>41592942
>>41592114
>making an actual story attached to it
Uhh, that's the worldbuilding right there.
I can whip up a summary of my setting in minutes. Basic tech level, what the culture roughly looks like, etc.
But when you separate the story like that, the characters and setting seem unconnected from each other. The internal and external motivations never combine in a believable way.
So what you end up with is the parts, except they don't support each other. If you, as the writer, are having trouble creating credible conflict in you cool setting, then maybe it's too clean.

>>41592276
This is pretty spot-on with my experience in the first half.
A good worldbuilding setup allows you to foreshadow in more ways.
So let's say you were writing a series. Your ultimate bad guy shows up in book one, but isn't recognized as such. But there he is, and by the end how he bent or broke the rules makes absolute sense.
In my case, stepping through the tech and how it's used pretty much laid out how to get from A to Z, and the whys. Hopefully, someone catches on and follows the false trails in the same way as the protags.
